SIMPLE: engage
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Engage
<hw>En*gage"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Engaged</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Engaging</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>engager</ets>; pref. <ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) +
<ets>gage</ets> pledge, pawn. See <er>Gage</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To put under pledge; to pledge; to place under obligations to do or
forbear doing something, as by a pledge, oath, or promise; to bind by
contract or promise.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I to thee <xex>engaged</xex> a
prince's word.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To gain for service; to bring in as associate or
aid; to enlist; <as>as, to <ex>engage</ex> friends to aid in a cause; to
<ex>engage</ex> men for service.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To gain over; to win and attach; to attract and
hold; to draw.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good nature <qex>engages</qex> everybody to him.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To employ the attention and efforts of; to occupy;
to engross; to draw on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus shall mankind his guardian care <qex>engage</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Taking upon himself the difficult task of <qex>engaging</qex> him
in conversation.</q> <rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To enter into contest with; to encounter; to bring
to conflict.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A favorable opportunity of <qex>engaging</qex> the enemy.</q>
<rj><qau>Ludlow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>To come into gear with; <as>as,
the teeth of one cogwheel <ex>engage</ex> those of another, or one part
of a clutch <ex>engages</ex> the other part</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Engage</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Engage
<hw>En*gage"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To promise or
pledge one's self; to enter into an obligation; to become bound; to
warrant.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How proper the remedy for the malady, I <qex>engage</qex> not.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To embark in a business; to take a part; to employ
or involve one's self; to devote attention and effort; to enlist;
<as>as, to <ex>engage</ex> in controversy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To enter into conflict; to join battle; <as>as, the
armies <ex>engaged</ex> in a general battle</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Mach.)</fld> <def>To be in gear, as two cogwheels
working together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Engaged</ent>⟦br⟧
